   <titles>
      <title>Illustration: Length of an Arrow</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>The length of the arrow joining <math>
                     <latex>P(x_1,\dots ,x_n)</latex>
                  </math> to <math>
                     <latex>Q(y_1,\dots ,y_n)</latex>
                  </math> is given by the formula</para.body>
            </para>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                     <img src="ims/ArrowLength_Illstrtn.gif"/>
                  </media>
               </para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>\Abs{ \overset{\longrightarrow}{PQ} }\ :=\ \text{dist}(P,Q)\ =\ \sqrt{(y_1-x_1)^2+\cdots +(y_n-x_n)^2}.</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>This means that the length of an arrow is defined to be the distance between its end points.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </body>
